niment generation task in which an existing MMO recording                   against Mref , the spectral mismatch will lead to noisy alignments. If,\n                                         is modified to match the user’s playing.                                           however, we ignore temporal regions (like silence) in Oacc that lack\n                                            Automatic musical accompaniment has a rich history of study that                prominent timing cues, we can focus on aligning the more “robust”\n                                         extends several decades (e.g. see [1]–[6] for representative samples).             parts and simply use linear interpolation in the less “robust” regions.\n                                         For non-improvised music, previous work generally assumes that the                 We propose a variant of DTW called Dense-Sparse DTW (DS-DTW)\n                                         accompaniment system has access to a musical score in a symbolic                   that aligns selected elements from one sequence (the “sparsified”\n                                         format like MIDI. However, for certain genres of music (such as                    sequence) against another (dense) sequence.\n                                         piano concertos), symbolic scores are not widely available and are                    DS-DTW fits into a broad corpus of work on DTW as a tool for\n                                         very time-consuming to create.                                                     alignment. Works in this area generally fall into one of two groups.\n                                            In this work, we explore a paradigm for automated piano concerto                The first group focuses on reducing the quadratic computation and\n                                         accompaniment in which a symbolic score is not needed. Instead, we                 memory costs of DTW. Some